## ✅ Better & Modern Approach (Recommended)

Using `isMounted` works, but **AbortController** is the modern, correct way.

### ✅ AbortController (Actually Cancels Fetch)

```js
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();

  const fetchData = async () => {
    try {
      const res = await fetch("/api/data", {
        signal: controller.signal
      });
      const data = await res.json();
      setData(data);
    } catch (err) {
      if (err.name !== "AbortError") {
        console.error(err);
      }
    }
  };

  fetchData();

  return () => {
    controller.abort();
  };
}, []);
```

✅ Actually stops the request  
✅ Cleaner  
✅ No memory leaks

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Explanation (IMPORTANT)

> The cleanup function in `useEffect` does not stop the async function. It only runs when the component unmounts and helps prevent state updates after unmount. The `isMounted` flag is used to ignore the result safely.

***

## ✅ One‑Line Answer (Perfect for Interview)

> The `return` in `useEffect` is a cleanup function that runs on unmount; it doesn’t stop the async call, but it prevents state updates after the component is unmounted.

***

